.TH erl 1 "erts 15.2.3" "Ericsson AB" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
erl \- Start the Erlang runtime system
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The \fIerl\fR program starts an Erlang runtime system. The exact details (for example, whether \fIerl\fR is a script or a program and which other programs it calls) are system-dependent.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIf you are using Erlang/OTP 25 or earlier on Windows and want to start an Erlang system with full shell support, you should use \fIwerl.exe\fR.  See the Erlang/OTP 25 documentation for details on how to do that.


.SS "erl <arguments>"

.PP
Starts an Erlang runtime system.

.PP
The arguments can be divided into \fIemulator flags\fR, \fIflags\fR, and \fIplain arguments\fR:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Any argument starting with character \fI+\fR is interpreted as an emulator flag.

.PP
As indicated by the name, emulator flags control the behavior of the emulator.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Any argument starting with character \fI-\fR (hyphen) is interpreted as a flag, which is to be passed to the Erlang part of the runtime system, more specifically to the \fIinit\fR system process, see \fIinit\fR.

.PP
The \fIinit\fR process itself interprets some of these flags, the \fIinit flags\fR. It also stores any remaining flags, the \fIuser flags\fR. The latter can be retrieved by calling \fIinit:get_argument/1\fR.

.PP
A small number of "-" flags exist, which now actually are emulator flags, see the description below.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Plain arguments are not interpreted in any way. They are also stored by the \fIinit\fR process and can be retrieved by calling \fIinit:get_plain_arguments/0\fR. Plain arguments can occur before the first flag, or after a \fI--\fR flag. Also, the \fI-extra\fR flag causes everything that follows to become plain arguments.

.RE

.PP
\fIExamples:\fR

.IP
.nf
% erl +W w -sname arnie +R 9 -s my_init -extra +bertie
(arnie@host)1> init:get_argument(sname).
{ok,[["arnie"]]}
(arnie@host)2> init:get_plain_arguments().
["+bertie"]

.fi

.PP
Here \fI+W w\fR and \fI+R 9\fR are emulator flags. \fI-s my_init\fR is an init flag, interpreted by \fIinit\fR. \fI-sname arnie\fR is a user flag, stored by \fIinit\fR. It is read by Kernel and causes the Erlang runtime system to become distributed. Finally, everything after \fI-extra\fR (that is, \fI+bertie\fR) is considered as plain arguments.

.IP
.nf
% erl -myflag 1
1> init:get_argument(myflag).
{ok,[["1"]]}
2> init:get_plain_arguments().
[]

.fi

.PP
Here the user flag \fI-myflag 1\fR is passed to and stored by the \fIinit\fR process. It is a user-defined flag, presumably used by some user-defined application.

.SS "Flags"

.PP
In the following list, init flags are marked "(init flag)". Unless otherwise specified, all other flags are user flags, for which the values can be retrieved by calling \fIinit:get_argument/1\fR. Notice that the list of user flags is not exhaustive, there can be more application-specific flags that instead are described in the corresponding application documentation.

-- (init flag)
.RS 2
Everything following 
\fI--\fR up to the next flag (\fI-flag\fR or \fI+flag\fR) is considered plain arguments and can be retrieved using \fIinit:get_plain_arguments/0\fR.

.RE

-Application Par Val
.RS 2
Sets the application configuration parameter 
\fIPar\fR to the value \fIVal\fR for the application \fIApplication\fR; see \fIapp(4)\fR and \fIapplication\fR.

.RE

-args_file FileName
.RS 2
Command-line arguments are read from the file 
\fIFileName\fR. The arguments read from the file replace flag '\fI-args_file FileName\fR' on the resulting command line.
.PP
The file \fIFileName\fR is to be a plain text file and can contain comments and command-line arguments. A comment begins with a \fI#\fR character and continues until the next end of line character. Backslash (\\) is used as quoting character. All command-line arguments accepted by \fIerl\fR are allowed, also flag \fI-args_file FileName\fR. Be careful not to cause circular dependencies between files containing flag \fI-args_file\fR, though.

.PP
The flag \fI-extra\fR is treated in special way. Its scope ends at the end of the file. Arguments following an \fI-extra\fR flag are moved on the command line into the \fI-extra\fR section, that is, the end of the command line following after an \fI-extra\fR flag.


.RE

-async_shell_start
.RS 2
The initial Erlang shell does not read user input until the system boot procedure has been completed (Erlang/OTP 5.4 and later). This flag disables the start synchronization feature and lets the shell start in parallel with the rest of the system.


.RE

-boot File
.RS 2
Specifies the name of the boot file, 
\fIFile.boot\fR, which is used to start the system; see \fIinit\fR. Unless \fIFile\fR contains an absolute path, the system searches for \fIFile.boot\fR in the current and \fI$ROOT/bin\fR directories.
.PP
Defaults to \fI$ROOT/bin/start.boot\fR.


.RE

-boot_var Var Dir
.RS 2
If the boot script contains a path variable 
\fIVar\fR other than \fI$ROOT\fR, this variable is expanded to \fIDir\fR. Used when applications are installed in another directory than \fI$ROOT/lib\fR; see \fIsystools:make_script/1,2\fR in SASL.

.RE

-code_path_cache
.RS 2
Enables the code path cache of the code server; see 
\fIcode\fR.

.RE

-compile Mod1 Mod2 ...
.RS 2
Compiles the specified modules and then terminates (with non-zero exit code if the compilation of some file did not succeed). Implies 
\fI-noinput\fR.
.PP
Not recommended; use \fIerlc\fR instead.


.RE

-config Config [Config ...]
.RS 2
Specifies the name of one or more configuration files, 
\fIConfig.config\fR, which is used to configure applications; see \fIapp(4)\fR and \fIapplication\fR. See the documentation for the configuration file format for a description of the configuration format and the order in which configuration parameters are read.

.RE

-configfd FD [FD ...]
.RS 2
Specifies the name of one or more file descriptors (called configuration file descriptors from here on) with configuration data for applications; see 
\fIapp(4)\fR and \fIapplication\fR. See the documentation for the configuration file format for a description of the configuration format and the order in which configuration parameters are read.
.PP
A configuration file descriptor will be read until its end and will then be closed.

.PP
The content of a configuration file descriptor is stored so that it can be reused when \fIinit:restart/0\fR or \fIinit:restart/1\fR is called.

.PP
The parameter \fI-configfd 0\fR implies \fI-noinput\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIt is not recommended to use file descriptors 1 (standard output), and 2 (standard error) together with \fI-configfd\fR as these file descriptors are typically used to print information to the console the program is running in.


.PP
Examples (Unix shell):

.IP
.nf
$ erl \\
-noshell \\
-configfd 3 \\
-eval \\
'io:format("~p~n",[application:get_env(kernel, logger_level)]),erlang:halt()' 3< \\
<(echo '[{kernel, [{logger_level, warning}]}].')
{ok,warning}

.fi

.IP
.nf
$ echo '[{kernel, [{logger_level, warning}]}].' > test1.config
$ echo '[{kernel, [{logger_level, error}]}].' > test2.config
$ erl \\
-noshell \\
-configfd 3 \\
-configfd 4 \\
-eval \\
'io:format("~p~n",[application:get_env(kernel, logger_level)]),erlang:halt()' \\
3< test1.config 4< test2.config
{ok,error}

.fi


.RE

-connect_all false
.RS 2
This flag is deprecated and has been replaced by the 
\fIkernel\fR application parameter \fIconnect_all\fR.

.RE

-cookie Cookie
.RS 2
Obsolete flag without any effect and common misspelling for 
\fI-setcookie\fR. Use \fI-setcookie\fR instead.

.RE

-detached
.RS 2
Starts the Erlang runtime system detached from the system console. Useful for running daemons and backgrounds processes. Implies 
\fI-noinput\fR.

.RE

-disable-feature feature
.RS 2
Disables the feature 
\fIfeature\fR in the runtime system. The special feature \fIall\fR can be used to disable all non permanent features.

.RE

-dist_listen true|false
.RS 2
Specifies whether this node should be listening for incoming distribution connections or not. By default a node will listen for incoming connections. Setting this option to 
\fIfalse\fR implies \fI-hidden\fR.

.RE

-emu_args
.RS 2
Useful for debugging. Prints the arguments sent to the emulator.


.RE

-emu_flavor emu|jit|smp
.RS 2
Start an emulator of a different flavor. Normally only one flavor is available, more can be added by building specific flavors. The currently available flavors are: 
\fIemu\fR and \fIjit\fR. The \fIsmp\fR flavor is an alias for the current default flavor. You can combine this flag with \fI--emu_type\fR. You can get the current flavor at run-time using \fIerlang:system_info(emu_flavor)\fR. (The emulator with this flavor must be built. You can build a specific flavor by doing \fImake FLAVOR=$FLAVOR\fR in the Erlang/OTP source repository.)

.RE

-emu_type Type
.RS 2
Start an emulator of a different type. For example, to start the lock-counter emulator, use 
\fI-emu_type lcnt\fR. You can get the current type at run-time using \fIerlang:system_info(build_type)\fR. (The emulator of this type must already be built. Use the \fIconfigure\fR option \fI--enable-lock-counter\fR to build the lock-counter emulator.)

.RE

-enable-feature feature
.RS 2
Enables the feature 
\fIfeature\fR in the runtime system. The special feature \fIall\fR can be used to enable all features.

.RE

-env Variable Value
.RS 2
Sets the host OS environment variable 
\fIVariable\fR to the value \fIValue\fR for the Erlang runtime system. Example:
.IP
.nf
% erl -env DISPLAY gin:0

.fi

.PP
In this example, an Erlang runtime system is started with environment variable \fIDISPLAY\fR set to \fIgin:0\fR.


.RE

-epmd_module Module
.RS 2
This flag is deprecated and has been replaced by the 
\fIkernel\fR application parameter \fIepmd_module\fR.

.RE

-erl_epmd_port Port
.RS 2
This flag is deprecated and has been replaced by the 
\fIkernel\fR application parameter \fIerl_epmd_node_listen_port\fR.

.RE

-eval Expr (init flag)
.RS 2
Makes 
\fIinit\fR evaluate the expression \fIExpr\fR; see \fIinit\fR.

.RE

-extra (init flag)
.RS 2
Everything following 
\fI-extra\fR is considered plain arguments and can be retrieved using \fIinit:get_plain_arguments/0\fR.

.RE

-heart
.RS 2
Starts heartbeat monitoring of the Erlang runtime system; see 
\fIheart\fR.

.RE

-hidden
.RS 2
Starts the Erlang runtime system as a hidden node, if it is run as a distributed node. Hidden nodes always establish hidden connections to all other nodes except for nodes in the same global group. Hidden connections are not published on any of the connected nodes, that is, none of the connected nodes are part of the result from 
\fInodes/0\fR on the other node. See also hidden global groups; \fIglobal_group\fR.

.RE

-hosts Hosts
.RS 2
Specifies the IP addresses for the hosts on which Erlang boot servers are running, see 
\fIerl_boot_server\fR. This flag is mandatory if flag \fI-loader inet\fR is present.
.PP
The IP addresses must be specified in the standard form (four decimal numbers separated by periods, for example, \fI"150.236.20.74"\fR). Hosts names are not acceptable, but a broadcast address (preferably limited to the local network) is.


.RE

-id Id
.RS 2
Specifies the identity of the Erlang runtime system. If it is run as a distributed node, 
\fIId\fR must be identical to the name supplied together with flag \fI-sname\fR or \fI-name\fR.

.RE

-init_debug
.RS 2
Makes 
\fIinit\fR write some debug information while interpreting the boot script.

.RE

-instr (emulator flag)
.RS 2
Selects an instrumented Erlang runtime system (virtual machine) to run, instead of the ordinary one. When running an instrumented runtime system, some resource usage data can be obtained and analyzed using the 
\fIinstrument\fR module. Functionally, it behaves exactly like an ordinary Erlang runtime system.

.RE

-loader Loader
.RS 2
Specifies the method used by 
\fIerl_prim_loader\fR to load Erlang modules into the system; see \fIerl_prim_loader\fR. Two \fILoader\fR methods are supported:

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIefile\fR, which means use the local file system, this is the default.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIinet\fR, which means use a boot server on another machine. The flags \fI-id\fR, \fI-hosts\fR and \fI-setcookie\fR must also be specified.

.RE

.PP
If \fILoader\fR is something else, the user-supplied \fILoader\fR port program is started.


.RE

-make
.RS 2
Makes the Erlang runtime system invoke 
\fImake:all()\fR in the current working directory and then terminate; see \fImake\fR. Implies \fI-noinput\fR.

.RE

-man Module
.RS 2
Displays the manual page for the Erlang module 
\fIModule\fR. Only supported on Unix.

.RE

-mode interactive | embedded
.RS 2
Modules are auto loaded when they are first referenced if the runtime system runs in 
\fIinteractive\fR mode, which is the default. In \fIembedded\fR mode modules are not auto loaded. The latter is recommended when the boot script preloads all modules, as conventionally happens in OTP releases. See \fIcode\fR.

.RE

-name Name
.RS 2
Makes the Erlang runtime system into a distributed node. This flag invokes all network servers necessary for a node to become distributed; see 
\fInet_kernel\fR. It also ensures that \fIepmd\fR runs on the current host before Erlang is started (see \fIepmd(1)\fR and the \fI-start_epmd\fR option) and that a magic cookie has been set (see -setcookie).
.PP
The node name will be \fIName@Host\fR, where \fIHost\fR is the fully qualified host name of the current host. For short names, use flag \fI-sname\fR instead.

.PP
If \fIName\fR is set to \fI\fIundefined\fR\fR the node will be started in a special mode optimized to be the temporary client of another node. The node will then request a dynamic node name from the first node it connects to. Read more in Dynamic Node Name.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRStarting a distributed node without also specifying \fI-proto_dist inet_tls\fR will expose the node to attacks that may give the attacker complete access to the node and in extension the cluster. When using un-secure distributed nodes, make sure that the network is configured to keep potential attackers out.



.RE

-no_epmd
.RS 2
Specifies that the distributed node does not need epmd at all.

.PP
This option ensures that the Erlang runtime system does not start epmd and does not start the \fIerl_epmd\fR process for distribution either.

.PP
This option only works if Erlang is started as a distributed node with the -proto_dist option using an alternative protocol for Erlang distribution which does not rely on epmd for node registration and discovery. For more information, see How to implement an Alternative Carrier for the Erlang Distribution.


.RE

-noinput
.RS 2
Ensures that the Erlang runtime system never tries to read any input. Implies 
\fI-noshell\fR.

.RE

-noshell
.RS 2
Starts an Erlang runtime system with no shell. This flag makes it possible to have the Erlang runtime system as a component in a series of Unix pipes.


.RE

-nostick
.RS 2
Disables the sticky directory facility of the Erlang code server; see 
\fIcode\fR.

.RE

-oldshell
.RS 2
Invokes the old Erlang shell from Erlang/OTP 3.3. The old shell can still be used.


.RE

-pa Dir1 Dir2 ...
.RS 2
Adds the specified directories to the beginning of the code path, similar to 
\fIcode:add_pathsa/1\fR. Note that the order of the given directories will be reversed in the resulting path.
.PP
As an alternative to \fI-pa\fR, if several directories are to be prepended to the code path and the directories have a common parent directory, that parent directory can be specified in environment variable \fIERL_LIBS\fR; see \fIcode\fR.


.RE

-pz Dir1 Dir2 ...
.RS 2
Adds the specified directories to the end of the code path, similar to 
\fIcode:add_pathsz/1\fR; see \fIcode\fR.

.RE

-path Dir1 Dir2 ...
.RS 2
Replaces the path specified in the boot script; see 
\fIscript(4)\fR.

.RE

-proto_dist Proto
.RS 2
Specifies a protocol for Erlang distribution:

inet_tcp
.RS 2
TCP over IPv4 (the default)


.RE

inet_tls
.RS 2
Distribution over TLS/SSL, See the Using SSL for Erlang Distribution User's Guide for details on how to setup a secure distributed node.


.RE

inet6_tcp
.RS 2
TCP over IPv6


.RE

.PP
For example, to start up IPv6 distributed nodes:

.IP
.nf
% erl -name test@ipv6node.example.com -proto_dist inet6_tcp

.fi


.RE

-remsh Node
.RS 2
Starts Erlang with a remote shell connected to 
\fINode\fR.
.PP
If no \fI-name\fR or \fI-sname\fR is given the node will be started using \fI-sname undefined\fR. If \fINode\fR does not contain a hostname, one is automatically taken from \fI-name\fR or \fI-sname\fR

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRBefore OTP-23 the user \fIneeded\fR to supply a valid \fI-sname\fR or \fI-name\fR for \fI-remsh\fR to work. This is still the case if the target node is not running OTP-23 or later.


.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe connecting node needs to have a proper shell with terminal emulation. This means that UNIX users must use an Erlang compiled with terminal capabilities and before Erlang/OTP 25 Windows users must use \fIwerl\fR.



.RE

-rsh Program
.RS 2
Specifies an alternative to 
\fIssh\fR for starting a slave node on a remote host; see \fIslave\fR.

.RE

-S Mod [Func [Arg1, Arg2, ...]] (init flag)
.RS 2
Makes 
\fIinit\fR call the specified function. \fIFunc\fR defaults to \fIstart\fR. The function is assumed to be of arity 1, taking the list \fI[Arg1,Arg2,...]\fR as argument, or an empty list if no arguments are passed. All further arguments occurring after this option are passed to the specified function as strings. Implies \fI-noshell\fR. See \fIinit\fR.

.RE

-run Mod [Func [Arg1, Arg2, ...]] (init flag)
.RS 2
Makes 
\fIinit\fR call the specified function. \fIFunc\fR defaults to \fIstart\fR. If no arguments are provided, the function is assumed to be of arity 0. Otherwise it is assumed to be of arity 1, taking the list \fI[Arg1,Arg2,...]\fR as argument. All arguments are passed as strings. See \fIinit\fR.

.RE

-s Mod [Func [Arg1, Arg2, ...]] (init flag)
.RS 2
Makes 
\fIinit\fR call the specified function. \fIFunc\fR defaults to \fIstart\fR. If no arguments are provided, the function is assumed to be of arity 0. Otherwise it is assumed to be of arity 1, taking the list \fI[Arg1,Arg2,...]\fR as argument. All arguments are passed as atoms. See \fIinit\fR.

.RE

-setcookie Cookie
.RS 2
Sets the magic cookie of the node to 
\fICookie\fR; see \fIerlang:set_cookie/1\fR. See see section Distributed Erlang in the Erlang Reference Manual for more details.

.RE

-setcookie Node Cookie
.RS 2
Sets the magic cookie for 
\fINode\fR to \fICookie\fR; see \fIerlang:set_cookie/2\fR.

.RE

-shutdown_time Time
.RS 2
Specifies how long time (in milliseconds) the 
\fIinit\fR process is allowed to spend shutting down Erlang applications in the system. If \fITime\fR milliseconds have elapsed, all processes still existing are killed. Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.

.RE

-sname Name
.RS 2
Makes the Erlang runtime system into a distributed node, similar to 
\fI-name\fR, but the host name portion of the node name \fIName@Host\fR will be the short name, not fully qualified.
.PP
This is sometimes the only way to run distributed Erlang if the Domain Name System (DNS) is not running. No communication can exist between nodes running with flag \fI-sname\fR and those running with flag \fI-name\fR, as node names must be unique in distributed Erlang systems.

.PP
If \fIName\fR is set to \fI\fIundefined\fR\fR the node will be started in a special mode optimized to be the temporary client of another node. The node will then request a dynamic node name from the first node it connects to. Read more in Dynamic Node Name.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRStarting a distributed node without also specifying \fI-proto_dist inet_tls\fR will expose the node to attacks that may give the attacker complete access to the node and in extension the cluster. When using un-secure distributed nodes, make sure that the network is configured to keep potential attackers out.



.RE

-start_epmd true | false
.RS 2
Specifies whether Erlang should start epmd on startup. By default this is 
\fItrue\fR, but if you prefer to start epmd manually, set this to \fIfalse\fR.
.PP
This only applies if Erlang is started as a distributed node, i.e. if \fI-name\fR or \fI-sname\fR is specified. Otherwise, epmd is not started even if \fI-start_epmd true\fR is given.

.PP
Note that a distributed node will fail to start if epmd is not running.


.RE

-version (emulator flag)
.RS 2
Makes the emulator print its version number. The same as 
\fIerl +V\fR.

.RE

.SS "Emulator Flags"

.PP
\fIerl\fR invokes the code for the Erlang emulator (virtual machine), which supports the following flags. The flags are read from left to right and later flags override the behavior of earlier flags.

+a size
.RS 2
Suggested stack size, in kilowords, for threads in the async thread pool. Valid range is 16-8192 kilowords. The default suggested stack size is 16 kilowords, that is, 64 kilobyte on 32-bit architectures. This small default size has been chosen because the number of async threads can be large. The default size is enough for drivers delivered with Erlang/OTP, but might not be large enough for other dynamically linked-in drivers that use the 
\fIdriver_async()\fR functionality. Notice that the value passed is only a suggestion, and it can even be ignored on some platforms.

.RE

+A size
.RS 2
Sets the number of threads in async thread pool. Valid range is 1-1024. The async thread pool is used by linked-in drivers to handle work that may take a very long time. Since OTP 21, the default Erlang/OTP distribution includes few linked-in drivers that use the async thread pool. Most of them have been migrated to dirty IO schedulers. Defaults to 1.


.RE

+B [c | d | i]
.RS 2
Option 
\fIc\fR makes \fICtrl-C\fR interrupt the current shell instead of invoking the emulator break handler. Option \fId\fR (same as specifying \fI+B\fR without an extra option) disables the break handler. Option \fIi\fR makes the emulator ignore any break signal.
.PP
If option \fIc\fR is used with \fIoldshell\fR on Unix, \fICtrl-C\fR will restart the shell process rather than interrupt it.


.RE

+c true | false
.RS 2
Enables or disables time correction:

true
.RS 2
Enables time correction. This is the default if time correction is supported on the specific platform.


.RE

false
.RS 2
Disables time correction.


.RE

.PP
For backward compatibility, the boolean value can be omitted. This is interpreted as \fI+c false\fR.


.RE

+C no_time_warp | single_time_warp | multi_time_warp
.RS 2
Sets time warp mode:

no_time_warp
.RS 2
No time warp mode (the default)


.RE

single_time_warp
.RS 2
Single time warp mode


.RE

multi_time_warp
.RS 2
Multi-time warp mode


.RE


.RE

+d
.RS 2
If the emulator detects an internal error (or runs out of memory), it, by default, generates both a crash dump and a core dump. The core dump is, however, not very useful as the content of process heaps is destroyed by the crash dump generation.

.PP
Option \fI+d\fR instructs the emulator to produce only a core dump and no crash dump if an internal error is detected.

.PP
Calling \fIerlang:halt/1\fR with a string argument still produces a crash dump. On Unix systems, sending an emulator process a \fISIGUSR1\fR signal also forces a crash dump.


.RE

+dcg DecentralizedCounterGroupsLimit
.RS 2
Limits the number of decentralized counter groups used by decentralized counters optimized for update operations in the Erlang runtime system. By default, the limit is 256.

.PP
When the number of schedulers is less than or equal to the limit, each scheduler has its own group. When the number of schedulers is larger than the groups limit, schedulers share groups. Shared groups degrade the performance for updating counters while many reader groups degrade the performance for reading counters. So, the limit is a tradeoff between performance for update operations and performance for read operations. Each group consumes 64 bytes in each counter.

.PP
Note that a runtime system using decentralized counter groups benefits from binding schedulers to logical processors, as the groups are distributed better between schedulers with this option.

.PP
This option only affects decentralized counters used for the counters that are keeping track of the memory consumption and the number of terms in ETS tables of type ordered_set with the write_concurrency option activated.


.RE

+e Number
.RS 2
Sets the maximum number of ETS tables. This limit is partially obsolete.


.RE

+ec
.RS 2
Forces option 
\fIcompressed\fR on all ETS tables. Only intended for test and evaluation.

.RE

+fnl
.RS 2
The virtual machine works with filenames as if they are encoded using the ISO Latin-1 encoding, disallowing Unicode characters with code points > 255.

.PP
For more information about Unicode filenames, see section Unicode Filenames in the STDLIB User's Guide. Notice that this value also applies to command-line parameters and environment variables (see section Unicode in Environment and Parameters in the STDLIB User's Guide).


.RE

+fnu[{w|i|e}]
.RS 2
The virtual machine works with filenames as if they are encoded using UTF-8 (or some other system-specific Unicode encoding). This is the default on operating systems that enforce Unicode encoding, that is, Windows MacOS X and Android.

.PP
