.RS 2
Can contain the port number to use when communicating with 
\fIepmd\fR. The default port works fine in most cases. A different port can be specified to allow nodes of independent clusters to co-exist on the same host. All nodes in a cluster must use the same \fIepmd\fR port number.

.RE

.SS "Signals"

.PP
On Unix systems, the Erlang runtime will interpret two types of signals.

SIGUSR1
.RS 2
A 
\fISIGUSR1\fR signal forces a crash dump.

.RE

SIGTERM
.RS 2
A 
\fISIGTERM\fR will produce a \fIstop\fR message to the \fIinit\fR process. This is equivalent to a \fIinit:stop/0\fR call.
.PP
Introduced in ERTS 8.3 (Erlang/OTP 19.3)


.RE

.PP
The signal \fISIGUSR2\fR is reserved for internal usage. No other signals are handled.

.SS "Configuration"

.PP
The standard Erlang/OTP system can be reconfigured to change the default behavior on startup.

The \&.erlang startup file
.RS 2
When Erlang/OTP is started, the system searches for a file named 
\fI.erlang\fR in the user's home directory and then \fIfilename:basedir(user_config, "erlang")\fR.
.PP
If an \fI.erlang\fR file is found, it is assumed to contain valid Erlang expressions. These expressions are evaluated as if they were input to the shell.

.PP
A typical \fI.erlang\fR file contains a set of search paths, for example:

.IP
.nf
io:format("executing user profile in $HOME/.erlang\\n",[]).
code:add_path("/home/calvin/test/ebin").
code:add_path("/home/hobbes/bigappl-1.2/ebin").
io:format(".erlang rc finished\\n",[]).

.fi


.RE


